**TL;DR: The Complete Princess Cut Engagement Ring Setting Guide**

A princess cut diamond engagement ring requires a setting designed specifically for its four 90-degree corners. The setting you choose affects corner protection, visual size, sparkle character, and metal durability. This guide covers every category — solitaire, pavé, halo, three-stone, bezel, cathedral, and vintage — with live Blue Nile prices, metal comparisons, and Farzana's ranked picks for each category.

**The rule that governs every setting choice:** V-tip prongs on all four corners are mandatory for princess cut diamonds. Any setting without four corner V-prongs transfers corner stress directly to the diamond. See [Princess Cut Solitaire Engagement Ring](https://diamondcritics.com/princess-cut-solitaire-engagement-ring/) for the full Corner Chip Risk analysis.

---

## Setting Categories at a Glance

| Setting Type | Price Range | V-prong Compatible | Best For |
|---|---:|---|---|
| Solitaire | $790–$1,635 | Yes (confirm) | Classic look, maximum stone visibility |
| Pavé Band | $1,325–$2,890 | Yes (corners still exposed) | Added sparkle, no side stones |
| French Pavé | $2,140–$3,925 | Yes | Maximum band brilliance |
| Hidden Halo | $1,255 | Yes | Maintains square profile |
| Round Halo | $2,000–$4,460 | No — buyer trap | Not recommended for princess |
| Bezel | $990–$4,625 | Yes (full corner protection) | Maximum durability, modern look |
| Three-Stone | $1,970–$4,510 | Yes | Statement ring, total carat weight |
| Cathedral | $1,635–$2,010 | Yes | Elevated presentation |
| Vintage/Milgrain | $1,190–$3,250 | Yes | Art Deco aesthetic |

