## Metal Comparison for Princess Cut Settings

| Metal | Price Multiplier vs 14k WG | Durability | Best Use |
|---|---|---|---|
| 14k Yellow Gold | 1× (baseline) | Good | Warm tone; G color looks white |
| 14k White Gold | 1× | Good | Neutral; re-plating rhodium every 2–3 years |
| 14k Rose Gold | 1× | Good | Warm-pink modern tone |
| 18k Yellow Gold | 1.2× | Softer | Richer yellow; scratches more easily |
| 18k White Gold | 1.2× | Softer | Same re-plating needed |
| Platinum | 1.4–1.6× | Excellent | Best for princess prong longevity; lifetime metal |

**Farzana's rule:** For princess cut, choose platinum when budget allows. V-prong durability on four corners is more critical than on round cuts — platinum prongs last 2–3× longer than 14k before re-tipping.

---

## Setting Decision Tree

1. **Active lifestyle / physical work?** → Bezel setting. Full corner protection. Stop here.
2. **Want the clean square look?** → Solitaire or hidden halo. Not round halo.
3. **Want sparkle on the band?** → Pavé (micropavé < riviera < french < scalloped by coverage intensity).
4. **Want to show total carat weight?** → Three-stone (marquise or emerald side stones).
5. **Vintage aesthetic?** → Milgrain lace or Art Deco fleur-de-lis.
6. **Maximum protection + sparkle?** → Bezel with channel set accent.

